This problem is substantially more difficult than the 1lyr case
because of the interface contact line between the layers.  Its
location on the center land is extremely sensitive to processing
conditions.  Just now the problem is set up for a flat-sided land
whose angle can be changed etc.    Follow this proceedure to
obtain a solution.  Note also that the parameters for this problem
have been consolidated at the top of the file "geometry" which is
used to generate your mesh.

To get a solution (the initial distribution here should be ready to
run to get you a solution.):

YOU MUST START WITH HIGH SURFACE TENSION (~0.1) ON THE INTERFACE
AND A 90 DEG. CONTACT ANGLE, THEN CONTINUE DOWN IN SURFACE TENSION.
But first get a fixed grid solution with the following boundary
conditions AND the "Initial Guess" card set to "zero": 


------
BC = VELO_NORMAL SS 23 0.
$$BC = KINEMATIC   SS      23       0.
$$BC = CAPILLARY   SS      23       {surface_tension1}  {vacuum}  0.
$$$BC = CA          NS    700       1.000    0.0   -1.0    0.0
B$$C = CA          NS    100       0.600    0.0    1.0    0.0

$$ Down the downstream Meniscus

BC = VELO_NORMAL SS 6 0.
$$BC = KINEMATIC   SS      6       0.
$$BC = CAPILLARY   SS      6       {surface_tension2}   0.0  0.
$$BC = SURFTANG_SCALAR    NS    400 {surface_tension2}

$$ Interface

BC = VELO_NORMAL SS 40 0.
$$BC = KINEMATIC   SS      40       0.
$$BC = CAPILLARY   SS      40       {.11}   0.0  0.
$$BC = SURFTANG_SCALAR    NS    260 {0.11}
$$BC = CA  NS 290 1.57 0. 1. 0.

---------


goma -a -i slot_input
cp soln.dat  contin.dat

Now set the "Intial Guess" card to "read" and change the
interface boundary conditions (between layers on sset 40) 
as follows:

--------
$$BC = VELO_NORMAL SS 40 0.
BC = KINEMATIC   SS      40       0.
BC = CAPILLARY   SS      40       {.11}   0.0  0.
BC = SURFTANG_SCALAR    NS    260 {0.11}
BC = CA  NS 290 1.57 0. 1. 0.
--------

Then run the following sequence:

    ~/.sun5/bin/goma -a -i slot_input -r 0.08 -n 40
     cp soln.dat contin.dat
    ~/.sun5/bin/goma -a -i slot_input -r 0.1
     cp soln.dat contin.dat
    ~/.sun5/bin/goma -a -i slot_input 

Now you have a solution to the moving interface problem with
a fixed external up- and downstream meniscus and a moving 
interface.  Note I chose the LAND to be flat between the
slots.   

To release the downstream free surface:

--------
$$ Down the downstream Meniscus

$$BC = VELO_NORMAL SS 6 0.
BC = KINEMATIC   SS      6       0.
BC = CAPILLARY   SS      6       {surface_tension2}   0.0  0.
BC = SURFTANG_SCALAR    NS    400 {surface_tension2}
------

Here you need run goma as follows:

   goma -a -i slot_input -r 0.1
   cp soln.dat contin.dat
   goma -a -i slot_input

   cp soln.dat contin.dat


Finally release the upstream meniscus the same way (SSET 23):

---------
$$BC = VELO_NORMAL SS 23 0.
BC = KINEMATIC   SS      23       0.
BC = CAPILLARY   SS      23       {surface_tension1}  {vacuum}  0.
BC = CA          NS    700       1.000    0.0   -1.0    0.0
BC = CA          NS    100       0.600    0.0    1.0    0.0

--------

Here the vacuume is set to -700 up inthe "geometry" file.   


Final note, when changing parameters here, you must take small steps and
look at where the internal contact separation line wants to locate.  
Just now it is very limited as the land is flat.  The next generation of
this model will round that land and allow the separation line to 
travel up into either channel.


Good luck!

PRS (7/3/97)

